WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
My name is Malcolm Barrett. I'm a clinical research data scientist at Teladoc Health.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
I'm an epidemiologist and I'm also an R developer. I use R packages every day in my work. They're

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.280
also fundamental to the way that I organize my code. And the reason for that is that R

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:27.000
packages are the fundamental unit of shareable code in R. They solve many of our problems

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:33.240
for us. They make our code more robust, easier to share, and much safer over time, whether

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:37.720
that's somebody that's using it in the future that we've shared it with, or it's just us

00:00:37.720 --> 00:00:43.299
in six months, right? Our code is less likely to break in that time because of the robustness

00:00:43.299 --> 00:00:48.840
of R packages. And yet many people, when they encounter the idea of writing R package, they

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:54.799
think, this is too advanced for me. This is beyond my scope. This is beyond my skill set.

00:00:54.799 --> 00:00:58.160
Many people also think that they don't have something to offer. They think that if they're

00:00:58.160 --> 00:01:03.599
not writing something like ggplot2 or dplyr, something that's really incredible, then they

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:09.339
don't have anything to offer, anything to share. I'd like to tell you a story that comes

00:01:09.339 --> 00:01:14.760
from Buddhism. Once there was a father and a son. And at some point, the father and the

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:22.080
son got separated. Here, their lives diverged dramatically. The father became quite wealthy.

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:28.120
He developed a huge estate and amassed a great amount of riches. The son, on the other hand,

00:01:28.120 --> 00:01:36.400
became absolutely destitute. He was embodying poverty. Later on in their lives, the son

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:42.440
actually stumbled upon the father's estate. Now, the son didn't recognize the father.

00:01:42.440 --> 00:01:47.320
The father had changed so much in his riches that he was unrecognizable. But the father,

00:01:47.320 --> 00:01:51.680
even though his son was draped in poverty, recognized the son immediately. He tried to

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:57.440
bring him into the house to say, look, look, you can have all of this. And the son thought

00:01:57.440 --> 00:02:01.220
he was crazy. He tried to run out of the house. He thought, this guy is nuts. I don't want

00:02:01.220 --> 00:02:07.199
anything to do with this. So the father sent his servants to go after the son and hire

00:02:07.199 --> 00:02:14.759
him instead as an employee of the estate. The son worked his way up from the very bottom

00:02:14.759 --> 00:02:20.279
until many years later to the very top of the estate. At this point, he's the right-hand

00:02:20.279 --> 00:02:28.759
man of his father. On his deathbed, the father finally reveals to the son who he is, that

00:02:28.759 --> 00:02:35.199
in fact, everything that's around him is already his. And in some versions of the story, at

00:02:35.199 --> 00:02:41.160
this point, the son says that he actually has already understood that. He has naturally

00:02:41.160 --> 00:02:49.039
come to understand that what surrounds him is his wealth, his treasure, something that

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:58.080
is of himself. This is a talk about why you already have the skill set from the techniques

00:02:58.080 --> 00:03:06.119
that you use every day in your data analysis to pursue the path of our package development.

00:03:06.119 --> 00:03:11.440
In a Zen text called the Sandokai, there's a saying, if you do not see the way, you do

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:17.460
not see it even as you walk on it. This is to say that we're actually always already

00:03:17.460 --> 00:03:23.720
perfect and complete, already ready. So in R, we might say, if you don't see the R package,

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:30.919
you do not see it even as you develop it. For instance, you already structure your project.

00:03:30.919 --> 00:03:34.839
Now an R package has a very specific structure that it uses. And yours might look something

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:41.039
like this, your project. I've got a data folder, a reports folder, a scripts folder, an analysis

00:03:41.039 --> 00:03:48.039
folder. Now an R package specifically uses a folder called R, with a capital R. It also

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:55.240
uses a data folder, just as it is. Instead of a report, we might have a vignette, a long

00:03:55.240 --> 00:04:01.080
form documentation, as well as a number of other files that are formal but help us do

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:07.759
things that we actually often do in our analysis. Describe it, test it, and provide information

00:04:07.759 --> 00:04:14.759
about how it works. The use of this package is really useful in connecting the abilities

00:04:15.119 --> 00:04:21.359
that we already have that we use in our work to this formalized structure of using an R

00:04:21.359 --> 00:04:27.320
package. So as you might imagine, one of the most useful functions that this package has

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:31.920
is to create a package, using the create package function. So here I'm creating a package

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:38.420
called zenart R packages. And it's laying out all of this infrastructure that I need

00:04:38.420 --> 00:04:42.880
to use an R package, and it's doing it all for me automatically. It's also communicating

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:49.880
to me very concretely, very simply, what it's actually doing, and if I need to do anything.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:57.279
One of the most important files that it creates is the description file. The description file

00:04:57.279 --> 00:05:01.839
is going to tell you what the package does, what it's called, who wrote it, who contributed

00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:07.799
to it, what the license is, and it might tell you some more about dependencies and more

00:05:07.799 --> 00:05:13.640
along those lines. It's also a really amazing file because it's sort of a golden ticket.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:18.720
It gives you access to many of the really excellent tools in the R ecosystem for developing

00:05:18.720 --> 00:05:25.720
R packages, tools like usethis and devtools. For instance, usethis also has a function

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:33.559
called create project. And while this uses a formalized structure, it's much simpler

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:38.859
compared to an R package. It does create an RStudio project, but it doesn't have a lot

00:05:38.859 --> 00:05:43.920
of this other top-level stuff that organizes an R package. Notably, it doesn't have a description

00:05:43.920 --> 00:05:50.600
file. But we can add one to it using use description. And what happens when I add a description

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:57.119
file to a project that actually isn't a package, usethis still treats it as if it is a package.

00:05:57.119 --> 00:05:59.880
And so that means that we can tap into some of the tools that we're going to talk about,

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:04.640
about writing tests and other tools that we're not going to talk about, like writing documentation,

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:11.359
quite easily because usethis and devtools will actually treat your project as if it's

00:06:11.359 --> 00:06:18.359
a package. You also already write R code. Now, your R code might look something like

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:23.720
this. Here I'm taking iris, I'm grouping it, and I'm summarizing it, and it's resulting

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:30.440
in a data frame. This is something that I do every day in my work. And if I use usethis,

00:06:30.440 --> 00:06:35.679
I can put this code in a formal place using useR. This will create an R folder for me

00:06:35.679 --> 00:06:40.200
if it doesn't exist already and put my code into it, as well as open up this file for

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:46.279
me to write code in. Instead of just writing my code plainly, I'm actually going to wrap

00:06:46.279 --> 00:06:51.160
it in a function, functions being what you would expect in R package to export. So here

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:58.040
I'm creating summarizeiris, and I'm putting it in the file that I just opened. Now, one

00:06:58.040 --> 00:07:01.679
of the things that's really great about having a package or a project with a description

00:07:01.679 --> 00:07:08.079
file in it is tapping into the devtools ecosystem. Devtools has this function called loadall that

00:07:08.079 --> 00:07:11.920
has a key binding in RStudio that makes it a little bit easier. And what it does is it

00:07:11.920 --> 00:07:16.399
looks in that R folder, and it's going to load the functions that are in your package

00:07:16.399 --> 00:07:22.839
or your project into your session as if you had sourced that, as if you had sourced an

00:07:22.839 --> 00:07:28.559
R code script. And so now I have summarizeiris available to me, and I can run it in my console

00:07:28.559 --> 00:07:35.559
or in another script quite easily. You may not realize it, but you also already declare

00:07:36.559 --> 00:07:42.480
your dependencies. For instance, if I have code like this, it often begins with a series

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:49.239
of library calls. And really what I'm saying is, for this code to work, I need the dplyr

00:07:49.239 --> 00:07:56.239
library, and I need the ggplot2 library. Otherwise, this function is not going to run correctly.

00:07:57.239 --> 00:08:01.920
In a package, we can declare dependency by using the use package function. So here I'm

00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:07.480
saying use package dplyr, use this as adding it to the description file, and then it's

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:12.200
telling me that I have something to do. Whenever I use a function from this package, I need

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:19.200
to preface it with dplyr, colon, colon. I need to really specify which namespace this

00:08:19.279 --> 00:08:24.279
function is coming from. And then I'll also do the same for ggplot2, because of course

00:08:24.279 --> 00:08:31.279
my code also depends on this package. So now when I have my function, I need to include

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:37.479
the names of these packages as well as the double colon. So this function ends up looking

00:08:37.479 --> 00:08:41.359
a little bit more like this, where I'm adding dplyr, colon, colon, and then the name of

00:08:41.359 --> 00:08:47.359
the function that comes from dplyr, and the same for ggplot2.

00:08:47.359 --> 00:08:52.760
What also is changing is my description file. What previously looked like this now has two

00:08:52.760 --> 00:08:59.760
extra lines. dplyr and ggplot are part of the import section. And this is where that

00:08:59.919 --> 00:09:05.400
magic happens when you install an R package. You'll notice that when you install an R package,

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:10.200
you don't have to manually go and install every other package that that package uses.

00:09:10.200 --> 00:09:15.760
R is smart enough to look at this file and install those packages for you. And so that's

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:20.840
exactly what happens when you install a package from CRAN or from GitHub or from another source.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:25.880
R will actually go and look for these packages and install them for you. You can also use

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:31.840
depth tools to install them manually using the installDepth function, which is extremely

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:35.320
useful.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:40.640
Now you may not realize this part in particular, but you also already test your code. This

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:44.840
might be one where you're thinking, wait a minute, I don't really even know what testing

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:50.400
your code means. I'm not a software engineer. I don't write unit tests when I do my analysis.

00:09:50.520 --> 00:09:56.159
I don't test my code, but actually we test our code every day, often in a situation like

00:09:56.159 --> 00:10:02.520
this. I've got this function, cleanData, and I'm giving it the iris dataset. And something

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:06.880
obviously has gone wrong here, right? It's giving me an error and I don't quite know

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:11.479
what the problem is. So I actually need to sit around and think about it a little bit.

00:10:11.479 --> 00:10:16.200
Usually at this point, I start fiddling around in my console to see if I can actually make

00:10:16.200 --> 00:10:21.239
it work, right? I will give it a different dataset or change a few things or look at

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:26.280
my code and really try to understand why isn't this working? So I go back and forth. I really

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:30.719
iterate through this process to try and get it working. And it turns out in this case,

00:10:30.719 --> 00:10:36.200
if for some reason I removed the fifth column, it actually works. My data is now clean. But

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:40.880
that just makes me think more, why is that? Right? And so I'm going to again go through

00:10:40.880 --> 00:10:46.080
that iterative process of figuring out what's wrong with my code. How can I get it to work?

00:10:46.159 --> 00:10:51.520
What do I expect it to look like? And what does it look like right now? What you're doing

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:58.780
is doing a unit test of your code. You just aren't writing it down. And so the process

00:10:58.780 --> 00:11:03.840
of writing unit tests is to formalize this iterative process of kicking the tire of our

00:11:03.840 --> 00:11:08.559
code to making sure that it works the way that we expect. Now, unfortunately, often

00:11:08.559 --> 00:11:14.599
the way we do this analysis is when it breaks. But writing unit tests helps you write code

00:11:14.599 --> 00:11:18.859
more robustly because it helps you kick the tires all around the car, not just in the

00:11:18.859 --> 00:11:28.559
tire that has a leak. The use test function will help you create a test in the right spot,

00:11:28.559 --> 00:11:32.119
set up all the infrastructure that you need from the test that package, which is one of

00:11:32.119 --> 00:11:37.479
the most popular testing libraries in R, put everything in its right place, open up for

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:42.119
this file for you, and set it up so that you can automate your tests. So if I go and I

00:11:42.119 --> 00:11:48.840
write the informal test that I just did in the command line directly in a test script,

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:54.719
I can now run the test function from DevTools, also which has a very convenient key binding

00:11:54.719 --> 00:12:00.239
in RStudio. It will load the package for me and will run all my tests. And now I can know

00:12:00.239 --> 00:12:06.080
if I make a change to my code that everything is still okay. I've got a green light still.

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:12.159
More importantly, if I don't, I know what's wrong and where it comes from. There are great

00:12:12.159 --> 00:12:20.979
many ways that you can use the R package system to extend what you already do in your analysis.

00:12:20.979 --> 00:12:26.219
But these are three really useful techniques that you can really get off the ground with.

00:12:26.219 --> 00:12:32.039
The first is using a description file. This lets you provide metadata about your project

